<font color="#FF0000">OUR WEAPONS TALK.</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 23 19:25:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Damn.<br><br>
Cook, <br><br>
I like that story.  I could feel it.  That's the kind of connection a Warrior has with his weapon.  Real passion. Your are the master of the story.  I advocate without question.  Between you and Ed you should copywright this whole site.<br><br>
I own historical weapons that I am connected with.  Not all just some.  Sold one once to a delta force weapons developer (active duty type) when I could no longer withstand his demands.  Hand made limited production 50/70.  I had bad dreams after the separation (real story).  Still feel remorse.<br><br>
Always talked to my aircraft.   Some were ladies and others were a bitch.  Still have nightmares about the bitches. When we were connected I could sweet talk them into anything. Talked one into staying together well above the airframe limit when I had a blue bandit on my ass one night.  Co-pilot kept yelling &quot;Boss shes going to come apart&quot;.  I told him shes talking to me.  He shut up.  He was crazy too.<br><br>
 They always gave me a feeling before something was going to go wrong.  I never named one, but the crew chief did.  Went out to fly one day and the crew chief was somewhere in orbit.  You know the beads, incense and other shit.  I had psychedelic fabric in the cockpit and incense burning on the floor.  He was damn proud of that plane.  Little sign hanging on the instrument panel reminding me to keep his girl clean.  Hell we were all crazy.  Doc Spatz thought our only problem was liking war.<br><br>
Ed<br><br>
I journeyed to Commanchee Peak today and reflected.  An afternoon in the hill country is restful.  I visited a spirit tree.  No visions, but peace.  There is power in the places.<br><br>

<p><code>--   (Silent Warrior) </code><p>


